The '''American Osteopathic Board of Dermatology (AOBD)''' is an organization that provides [[board certification]] to qualified [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|Doctors of Osteopathic Medicine]] (D.O.) who specialize in the medical and surgical treatment of disorders of the skin ([[dermatologists]]). The board is one of 18 [[Specialty (medicine)|medical specialty]] certifying boards of the [[American Osteopathic Association Bureau of Osteopathic Specialists]] approved by the [[American Osteopathic Association]] (AOA),<ref>{{cite web|title=AOA Specialty Certifying Boards|url=https://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/development/aoa-board-certification/Pages/aoa-specialty-boards.aspx|publisher=American Osteopathic Association|accessdate=13 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hwic.org/experts/details.php?id=3113 |title=American Osteopathic Board of Dermatology |author= |year= 2011|work= |publisher=Health Workforce Information Center |accessdate=13 September 2012 }}</ref> and was established in 1945.<ref>{{cite web|title=Overview of AOBD|url=http://www.aobd-derm.org/category/general-information/|publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Dermatology |accessdate=13 September 2012}}</ref> The AOBD is one of two certifying boards for dermatologists in the United States. The other certifying authority is the [[American Board of Dermatology]], a member board of the [[American Board of Medical Specialties]]. As of 2011, 396 osteopathic physicians held active certification with the AOBD.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ayres|first=Ronald E|coauthors=S Scheinthal, C Gross, and E Bell.|title=Changes to Osteopathic Specialty Board Certification|journal=Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|year=2012|month=April|volume=112|issue=4|pages=226â€“231|url=http://www.jaoa.org/content/112/4/226.full.pdf+html|accessdate=26 August 2012}}</ref> In addition to the fellows of the American Board of Dermatology, board certified osteopathic dermatologists are eligible for admission into the American Society for Mohs Surgery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mohssurgery.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=3301 |title=Fellow Member |author= |date= |work= |publisher=American Society for Mohs Surgery |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> 

==Board certification==
Initial certification is available to osteopathic dermatologists who have successfully completed an AOA-approved [[medical residency|residency]] in dermatology, two years of practice, successful completion of clinical and written exams.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aobd-derm.org/2012/02/12/certification-requirements/ |title=Requirements for Certification |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Dermatology |accessdate=13 September 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aobd-derm.org/2012/02/12/certification-exam-summary/ |title=Certification Exam Summary |author= |year= 2012|work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Dermatology |accessdate=13 September 2012 }}</ref> Diplomates of the American Osteopathic Board of Dermatology requires osteopathic dermatologists to renew their certification every ten years to avoid expiration of their board certified status.<ref name="castle">{{cite web |url=http://www.castleconnolly.com/resources/osteopathic.cfm
 |title=Medical Boards: Osteopathic |author= |date=2012 |work= |publisher=Castle Connolly Medical Ltd. |accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref>

==Subspecialties==
The AOBD also oversees examinations for osteopathic dermatologists that seek to subspecialize in the fields of [[Mohs micrographic surgery]] and [[dermatopathology]].<ref name="castle"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aobd-derm.org/2012/05/31/eligibility-requirements-for-examination-in-dermatopathology/ |title=Eligibility Requirements for Examination in Dermatopathology |author= |year= 2012|work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Dermatology |accessdate=13 September 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aobd-derm.org/2012/08/10/eligibility-requirements-for-certification-in-mohs-micrographic-surgery/ |title=Eligibility Requirements for Examination in Mohs Micrographic Surgery |author= |year= 2012|work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Dermatology |accessdate=13 September 2012 }}</ref>

